North Sea wind farms produce 21 percent more electricity
The wind farms on the German North Sea have supplied 11.51 terawatt hours of electricity to the grid in the first six months of the year.
This is a 21 percent increase on the same period last year, said Bayreuth-based Tennet.
Tennet is responsible for the transmission of North Sea current to the mainland and for its transmission through the German electricity network.
The wind farms in the Baltic Sea, which are not part of Tennet's network area, have supplied a further 2,22 terawatt hours (TWh).
The total amount of wind power from the North and Baltic Seas thus amounts to 13,73 TWh, compared to 11,64 TWh in the first half of 2019.
The harvesting of offshore wind accounts for almost 19 percent of all wind power in Germany, about four percentage points more than a year ago.
New wind farms provide more generation capacity
The increased contribution of offshore wind energy is due to higher generation capacities, in addition to wind conditions, due to the addition of new wind farms to the grid in the last 12 months.
If the 1,270 wind turbines in the North Sea were all running at full power at the same time, they could generate an estimated 6.7 gigawatts of electricity.
The transmission capacity is sufficient for this, Tennet says, at 7.1 gigawatts.
By 2030, it is to rise to 17 gigawatts in the German North Sea.
"In Germany and the Netherlands, we will invest €20 billion by then in expanding offshore grid connections", said Tim Meyerjürgens, CEO of Tennet.
In reality, even offshore wind farms cannot reach their full capacity, but only about 40 percent.
The previous record day this year was January 2, when the North Sea wind farms generated more than six gigawatts of electricity.
On average, the North Sea wind turbines produce about 2.5 to 3.0 gigawatts of electricity, equivalent to three to four nuclear power plants.
This could power almost seven million households.
