Fleetwood Mac co-founder Peter Green has died.
His life was like a roller coaster ride: after a quick climb with Fleetwood Mac, it went downhill and then slowly up again.
Now blues rock guitarist Peter Green has died at the age of 73.
Genius guitarist, drug addict, cult following, co-founder of Fleetwood Mac, Peter Green, is dead.
He died peacefully in his sleep at the age of 73, family members said in an official statement on Saturday, with a further statement to be announced in the coming days.
Top musicians like Peter Frampton have praised Green as one of the best blues and rock guitarists.
Mick Fleetwood spoke in an emotional reaction of a "monumental loss" for all past and present members of the band Fleetwood Mac.
Drummer Fleetwood and guitarist Green formed the now legendary band in London in 1967, and his dream instrumental hit "Albatross" is still memorable.
The musician's life ("The End Of The Game", "In The Skies") was like a roller coaster ride.
With Fleetwood Mac, Green experienced a rapid rise - the band celebrated their greatest successes but then without him.
One of the reasons for the dispute was that Green wanted to donate all the group's profits to charity.
He began to appear in broad robes and with a large crucifix.
Mental problems are also said to have played a role.
Green left the band in 1970, just three years after its formation.
There was a social decline.
The blues-rock guitarist suffered from drug abuse and schizophrenia, biographers reported.
For a long time, Green was treated in a psychiatric ward.
For much of the 1970s, the musician disappeared from the scene.
He is said to have lived on the streets for a time, worked as a cemetery gardener and spent time in an Israeli kibbutz.
Green was born in 1946 into a Jewish working-class family in Bethnal Green, London.
He was already a fan of American blues musicians like B.B. King and Muddy Waters.
At the age of eleven, he learned his first guitar strings.
At the age of 15, the teenager began playing guitar professionally and five years later got the chance to perform as lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners.
A little later, he was hired as a replacement for his idol Eric Clapton in the Bluesbreakers.
In the midst of the blues boom, Green formed Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 along with fellow Bluesbreakers Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
Green's song "Albatross" gave the group their first number one hit in the winter of 1968/69 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
But his rapid rise soon revealed its dark side: Green was not able to resist the media hype, his experiments with the drug LSD became more extreme.
He later commented in an interview on his life between music and addiction: "The worst thing that ever happened to me in my life was drugs - the best thing was landing a number one hit".
Toward the end of the decade, Green achieved surprising success in 1979 with a religiously-inspired album.
Fleetwood Mac, meanwhile, were swimming without him in a new formation on a wave of success.
Their 1977 album "Rumours" sold over 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various minor solo successes, Green did not make a major comeback until 1996 when he started again with a group of musicians friends.
The British Daily Telegraph reported at the time that a rock star had returned to Earth.
Green released several albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group before the band disbanded in 2004.
To music experts, he was already a blues legend in his lifetime - and with his gentle sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
